P05: {
  title: "Introduction to adeno-associated virus-based gene therapy",
  context: "Below, we will detail very relevant information for you to understand the most important aspects of the gene therapy that this study addresses. Please read all the information contained in the dropdowns first, before answering the question.",
  
  contextDropdown1: "<details onclick='closeContextDetails(this)' style='margin-bottom:16px;border:2px solid #3b82f6;border-radius:8px;padding:16px;background:#dbeafe;'><summary style='cursor:pointer;font-weight:600;font-size:16px;color:#0f2e6a;list-style:none;display:flex;align-items:center;'><span style='margin-right:8px;'>‚ñ∏</span> What does this gene therapy consist of?</summary><div style='margin-top:12px;padding-left:24px;'>‚Ä¢ It is based on the use of adeno-associated vectors (AAV) which are harmless viruses that have been modified in a laboratory to act as carriers for potential treatments.<br><br>‚Ä¢ It allows administering a single dose that would introduce new DNA into a large number of your brain cells (neurons) with the objective of permanently preventing the production of the prion protein in these cells.</div></details>",
  
  contextDropdown2: "<details onclick='closeContextDetails(this)' style='margin-bottom:16px;border:2px solid #3b82f6;border-radius:8px;padding:16px;background:#dbeafe;'><summary style='cursor:pointer;font-weight:600;font-size:16px;color:#0f2e6a;list-style:none;display:flex;align-items:center;'><span style='margin-right:8px;'>‚ñ∏</span> How does this gene therapy work?</summary><div style='margin-top:12px;padding-left:24px;'>‚Ä¢ The modified virus acts as a \\\"transport vehicle\\\" that carries genetic instructions in the form of DNA to the neurons in the brain.<br><br>‚Ä¢ Once inside the brain cells (neurons), these new instructions permanently \\\"turn off\\\" the production of the prion protein.<br><br>‚Ä¢ By not producing the prion protein, the development of the disease is prevented.</div></details>",
  
  contextDropdown3: "<details onclick='closeContextDetails(this)' style='margin-bottom:16px;border:2px solid #3b82f6;border-radius:8px;padding:16px;background:#dbeafe;'><summary style='cursor:pointer;font-weight:600;font-size:16px;color:#0f2e6a;list-style:none;display:flex;align-items:center;'><span style='margin-right:8px;'>‚ñ∏</span> More relevant information about this gene therapy</summary><div style='margin-top:12px;padding-left:24px;'>‚Ä¢ Single administration (does not require repeated doses).<br><br>‚Ä¢ Probably permanent and irreversible effect.<br><br>‚Ä¢ Has shown encouraging results in animal studies, including significant reduction of the problematic protein and absence of major harmful effects during the follow-up period.<br><br>‚Ä¢ Still in an experimental phase (not approved for clinical use).</div></details>",
  
  contextDropdown4: "<details onclick='closeContextDetails(this)' style='margin-bottom:16px;border:2px solid #3b82f6;border-radius:8px;padding:16px;background:#dbeafe;'><summary style='cursor:pointer;font-weight:600;font-size:16px;color:#0f2e6a;list-style:none;display:flex;align-items:center;'><span style='margin-right:8px;'>‚ñ∏</span> Other aspects to consider</summary><div style='margin-top:12px;padding-left:24px;'>‚Ä¢ Administration is performed intravenously, a routine and well-tolerated procedure similar to any hospital injection.<br><br>‚Ä¢ As with any experimental therapy, there may be side effects that are still unknown.<br><br>‚Ä¢ Being in the research phase, long-term safety data in humans ‚Äîthe possibility of more or less serious side effects years after receiving treatment‚Äî are limited.<br><br>‚Ä¢ Although it has worked very well in animals, it is unknown whether it will be effective in humans. The evaluation of both the efficacy and safety of the treatment is precisely what will be studied in the clinical trial.<br><br>‚Ä¢ Although highly unlikely, potential hereditary effects in people of reproductive age cannot be ruled out.<br><br>‚Ä¢ By using AAV vectors, this therapy could limit your future participation in other experimental treatments that use similar vectors, due to the development of immunity against these viruses. However, this drawback could have a solution in the future. Additionally, the effects of permanently preventing prion protein production would be irreversible once the treatment is administered.</div></details>",
  
  question: "After having read and understood this information, what is your first impression of this type of gene therapy?",
  options: {
    "1": "Very negative",
    "2": "Negative",
    "3": "Neutral", 
    "4": "Positive",
    "5": "Very positive",
    "6": "I don't have sufficient knowledge to form an opinion"
  }
},
